{"id":"quant-ph/0410169","submitter":"Paolo Perinotti Dr.","authors":"Giacomo Mauro D'Ariano and Paolo Perinotti","title":"Efficient universal programmable quantum measurements","comments":"4 pages, RevTex4","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 94, 090401 (2005)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.94.090401","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  A universal programmable detector is a device that can be tuned to perform\nany desired measurement on a given quantum system, by changing the state of an\nancilla. With a finite dimension d for the ancilla only approximate universal\nprogrammability is possible, with \"size\" d=f(1/e) increasing function of the\n\"accuracy\" 1/e. In this letter we show that, much better than the exponential\nsize known in the literature, one can achieve polynomial size. An explicit\nexample with linear size is also presented. Finally, we show that for covariant\nmeasurements exact programmability is feasible.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 21 Oct 2004 15:43:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
